posts.com:
>>128652030
Nope, that's how FIFA does FFP. It's dumb. Obviously a lot of clubs physically do instalments because they don't have a sugar daddy willing to drop £100m on a player. So the money has to come 'from the club' and even if you get a sugar daddy, if your club doesn't earn enough to cover the cost of the player even with a 10 year contract, you can't do it. But Chelsea could. It is super dumb.
>what are they even speculating about
Because the (claim) is that if Chelsea fail to make Top 4 it will actually be an issue. So taking a risk with a guy who might cost then £15m a year or whatever, could be the difference between breaking and complying. If you were 100% going to make Top 4, they probably would do it.

The other thing is from a FFP perspective, the money you RECEIVE for a player is considered instantaneous. So you sell a player for £100m but it is going to be paid £33.3m over three years? FFP counts it as getting £100m right smack then. That's to stop clubs from spreading instalments over 5 years to 'pad' their income because FFP only counts the last 3 years or something.

It's all really dumb but Chelsea have found a loophole and are exploiting it to the max. So much so UEFA is banning it in the summer. So they gotta make a decision. This might be the only time they can afford to do it with Enzo, but if they fail to get Top 4 they could be fucked. They might be hoping to offload a load of players as well.

>20 years without l'Avvocato

20 years have passed but it stil seems like yesterday.

On 24 January 2003 Gianni Agnelli left us, and his story immediately became legend.

The legend of one of the greatest entrepreneurs Italy has ever known, the story of one of the most multifaceted, charming and iconic personalities of an entire nation.

For us, however, l'Avvocato was - and always will be - something more, because of what he achieved and how he achieved it.

Gianni Agnelli was a great president, a guiding light, a beacon, an example of style, an embodiment of love for Juve. Agnelli was full of surprises - on the phone, with players and coaches, on the pitch, where he almost always showed up unannounced. Not only a trendsetter in how he dressed, also how he spoke was unique - his comments, intelligent and witty, always offered a fresh perspective, something to smile about, and very often to reflect on.

20 years may have passed, but we still miss l'Avvocato every day.

posts.com:
Hi, /sumo/, first time poster here, and not terribly familiar. I like sumo, especially how it's tied to Shinto tradition, and isn't overtly commercialized or only "just a sport."

An observation, however: Sumo training seems way too focused on ineffective traditions. Not that there's anything wrong with bodyweight exercises, but it appears they focus way too much on high-repetition aerobic activity. It's an anaerobic sport, and their training should reflect that.

Is there a practical explanation for this, or is it all
>muh tradition
Could an innovative stable trainer dominate by having his sumotori focus more on things like powerlifting and explosive exercises, and ditching all the kata?

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>128619002
The biggest part of traditional sumo training is practice bouts and chest lending. Practice bouts should be self explanatory. Chest lending is when a senior wrestler lets a junior charge against him repeatedly, over and over, until the junior is completely worn out and the senior is satisfied in their technique and that they're not quitting early. So it's a large number of repetitions of the anaerobic activity in the bout. The rest, like pole striking or forward shuffling, are for practicing of technique.

A lot of stables these days also incorporate actual weightlifting, either at a local gym or with equipment in the stable itself, and the number of stables incorporating weight training is steadily growing. The hardline traditionalists are usually limited to the really small ones or the ones with only lower division guys, and even then they'll frequently train with big/more senior stables of the same ichimon.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>128619249
Thank you, good to know.

I'm aware that practice bouts are a major part of training, and this would be more useful than anything else; not just for developing technique, but also for physical conditioning. But there are limitations to how much strength you can develop from just wrestling as opposed to properly heavy, low-rep compound weight-training.

It's just that whenever I've looked at sumo training, it seems like there's a lot of endurance work, which seems almost counter-productive, since the length of a match is measured in seconds.
